# Pattern: Flow-Based Layout States

This document describes a **component-level layout pattern**.
It is not a global rule.

Use this pattern only when a component must adapt
between stacked and side-by-side layouts safely.

---

## Concept

The component has two **flow states** based on available inline size.

### Flow States

- **flow-vertical**
  - Content flows top → bottom
  - Media appears above content
  - Default and fallback behavior
  - May participate in cross-item alignment (e.g. subgrid)

- **flow-horizontal**
  - Content flows left → right
  - Media appears beside content
  - Only used when the component can be measured safely
  - Component owns its internal layout
  - Opts out of cross-item alignment

These states are **mutually exclusive** and **closed**.

Fallback always maps to **flow-vertical**.

---

## When to Use

Use flow-based states when:

- Component has media + content
- Side-by-side layout is desirable but not always safe
- Content length and font size are variable
- Predictable degradation is required

Do not use this pattern for:

- Simple UI primitives
- Purely decorative elements
- Components with a single layout structure

